{"title_page": "Hakea hastata", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|image = \n|genus = Hakea\n|species = hastata\n|authority = [[Laurence Haegi|Haegi]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea hastata'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/70406 |website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n|range_map = Hakea hastataDistMap59.png\n|range_map_caption = Occurrence data from [[Australasian Virtual Herbarium|AVH]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Hakea hastata''''' is a shrub in the family [[Proteaceae]] and is  [[endemism|endemic]] to southern Western Australia.   \nIt is an open, upright shrub with light green leaves, branches covered in dense hairs and white flowers in spring.\n==Description==\n''Hakea hastata'' is an erect open shrub typically grows to a height of {{convert|1.5|to|3|m|ft|1}}.<ref name=FloraBase/> It is sparingly branched with branchlets that are densely covered in pale brown hairs. The pale green leaves have a narrowly to broadly ovate shape and a length of {{convert|2|to|4.7|cm|in|1}} and a width of {{convert|9|to|24|mm|in|3}} with one to three longitudinal nerves.<ref name=sa>{{cite web|url=http://www.flora.sa.gov.au/efsa/lucid/Hakea/key/Australian%20Hakea%20species/Media/Html/Hakea_hastata.htm|title=''Hakea hastata''|accessdate=25 October 2018|work=Electronic Flora of South Australia|publisher=[[Government of South Australia]]}}</ref> It blooms from September to October and produces white flowers.<ref name=FloraBase/> The solitary [[inflorescence]]s contain  18 to 22 flowers with a cream-white coloured [[perianth]]. After flowering woody fruits form that have an obliquely ovate to broadly ovate shape and are {{convert|1.6|to|2.0|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|0.9|to|1.2|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} wide with an obscure beak. The blackish brown seeds have an obliquely ovate or elliptic shape with a wing down one side.<ref name=sa/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIt was first formally described by the botanist Laurence Haegi in 1999 in the work ''Appendix: Hakea. Flora of Australia'' by Haegi, W.R.Barker, R.M.Barker and A.J.Wilson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/http://id.biodiversity.org.au/node/apni/2903404#names|title=''Hakea hastata'' Haegi|accessdate=25 October 2018|work=Atlas of Living Australia|publisher=[[Global Biodiversity Information Facility]]}}</ref>\nThe [[botanical name|specific epithet]] is from the [[Latin]] word ''hastata'' meaning ''spear-like'' referring to the spear-head shape of the leaves.<ref name=sa/>\n\n==Distribution==\nIt is [[endemism|endemic]] an area in the [[Wheatbelt (Western Australia)|Wheatbelt]] and [[Great Southern (Western Australia)|Great Southern]] regions of [[Western Australia]] from around [[Pingelly, Western Australia|Pingelly]] in the north to [[Albany, Western Australia|Albany]] in the south and has a scattered distribution. The shrub is found on and around hills and grows in sandy, loamy or clay soils that can contain gravel.<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Hakea hastata''|id=16907}}</ref> It is usually part of a heath understorey community in ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' woodlands.<ref name=sa/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q18079918}}\n\n[[Category:Hakea|hastata]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1999]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|image = \n|genus = Hakea\n|species = hastata\n|authority = [[Laurence Haegi|Haegi]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea hastata'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/70406 |website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n|range_map = Hakea hastataDistMap59.png\n|range_map_caption = Occurrence data from [[Australasian Virtual Herbarium|AVH]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Hakea hastata''''' is a shrub in the family [[Proteaceae]]  [[endemism|endemic]] to southern Western Australia.  \n\n==Description==\nThe erect open shrub typically grows to a height of {{convert|1.5|to|3|m|ft|1}}.<ref name=FloraBase/> It is sparingly branched with branchlets that are densely covered in pale brown hairs. The pale green leaves have a narrowly to broadly ovate shape and a length of {{convert|2|to|4.7|cm|in|1}} and a width of {{convert|9|to|24|mm|in|3}} with one to three longitudinal nerves.<ref name=sa>{{cite web|url=http://www.flora.sa.gov.au/efsa/lucid/Hakea/key/Australian%20Hakea%20species/Media/Html/Hakea_hastata.htm|title=''Hakea hastata''|accessdate=25 October 2018|work=Electronic Flora of South Australia|publisher=[[Government of South Australia]]}}</ref> It blooms from September to October and produces white flowers.<ref name=FloraBase/> The solitary [[inflorescence]]s contain  18 to 22 flowers with a cream-white coloured [[perianth]]. After flowering woody fruits form that have an obliquely ovate to broadly ovate shape and are {{convert|1.6|to|2.0|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|0.9|to|1.2|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} wide with an obscure beak. The blackish brown seeds have an obliquely ovate or elliptic shape with a wing down one side.<ref name=sa/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIt was first formally described by the botanist Laurence Haegi in 1999 in the work ''Appendix: Hakea. Flora of Australia'' by Haegi, W.R.Barker, R.M.Barker and A.J.Wilson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/http://id.biodiversity.org.au/node/apni/2903404#names|title=''Hakea hastata'' Haegi|accessdate=25 October 2018|work=Atlas of Living Australia|publisher=[[Global Biodiversity Information Facility]]}}</ref>\nThe [[botanical name|specific epithet]] is from the [[Latin]] word ''hastata'' meaning ''spear-like'' referring to the spear-head shape of the leaves.<ref name=sa/>\n\n==Distribution==\nIt is [[endemism|endemic]] an area in the [[Wheatbelt (Western Australia)|Wheatbelt]] and [[Great Southern (Western Australia)|Great Southern]] regions of [[Western Australia]] from around [[Pingelly, Western Australia|Pingelly]] in the north to [[Albany, Western Australia|Albany]] in the south and has a scattered distribution. The shrub is found on and around hills and grows in sandy, loamy or clay soils that can contain gravel.<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Hakea hastata''|id=16907}}</ref> It is usually part of a heath understorey community in ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' woodlands.<ref name=sa/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q18079918}}\n\n[[Category:Hakea|hastata]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1999]]\n", "name_user": "Allthingsnative", "label": "safe", "comment": "Expand lede", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hakea_hastata"}
